<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-07-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-07-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="365" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Porter</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-07-06"><hi rend="italic">July 6, 1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 687.]</seg></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your two cables concerning our
                                attitude in China were received on the 2d<note n="2" xml:id="d365fn2">Printed, ante.</note> and 4th<note n="3" xml:id="d365fn3">Printed, <ref target="#pg_299">p.
                                    299</ref>.</note> (dated 2d and 3d) instant and communicated
                                without delay to the minister of foreign affairs, who appreciates
                                these communications and is thankful for being kept informed of our
                                intentions.</p>
                            <p>I have the honor to be, etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Horace
                                Porter.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>